  "local_port": 60300,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why is my keyboard's laptop locked? How do I fix it?",
  "response": "If your laptop keyboard is locked or not functioning properly, it could be due to various reasons. Here are some common causes and how you can fix them:\n\n### Possible Causes and Fixes:\n\n1. **Function Key Lock (Fn Lock)**:\n   - **Cause**: Some laptops have a function key (Fn) lock that disables the keyboard.\n   - **Fix**: Look for an \"Fn\" key on your keyboard, as well as a lock symbol (usually on one of the function keys, such as F1-F12). Press \"Fn\" + \"Esc\" or the appropriate function key to toggle the lock.\n\n2. **Sticky Keys**:\n   - **Cause**: Sticky Keys or other accessibility features may be turned on.\n   - **Fix**: Press the \"Shift\" key five times in a row to toggle Sticky Keys off. Alternatively, check the Settings under Ease of Access (Windows) or Accessibility (Mac) to disable Sticky Keys.\n\n3. **Keyboard Driver Issues**:\n   - **Cause**: Outdated or corrupted keyboard drivers can prevent the keyboard from working properly.\n   - **Fix**: \n     - On **Windows**: Right-click on the Start menu and go to Device Manager. Expand the \"Keyboards\" section, right-click your keyboard, and select \"Update driver\". If that doesn't work, you can also try uninstalling the driver and then restart your laptop to reinstall it automatically.\n     - On **Mac**: Check for system updates by going to Apple Menu > System Preferences > Software Update.\n\n4. **External Device Interference**:\n   - **Cause**: An external device or peripheral may interfere with your laptop's keyboard.\n   - **Fix**: Disconnect any external keyboards or USB devices. Restart your laptop and check if the internal keyboard starts working again.\n\n5. **Keyboard Settings or Language Issues**:\n   - **Cause**: The keyboard layout might have changed.\n   - **Fix**: Check the keyboard settings in the control panel or system preferences to ensure the correct language and layout are selected.\n\n6. **Hardware Issues**:\n   - **Cause**: There could be a physical issue with the keyboard itself, like damage or debris.\n   - **Fix**: Inspect the keyboard for any physical damage or stuck keys. If you find any debris, carefully clean it. If it's still not working, you may need to seek professional help or replace the keyboard.\n\n7. **Restart Your Laptop**:\n   - Sometimes, a simple restart can resolve many temporary issues.\n\n8. **Check for BIOS/UEFI Settings**:\n   - **Cause**: In rare cases, keyboard functionality may be disabled in BIOS settings.\n   - **Fix**: Enter BIOS/UEFI on startup (usually by pressing F2, F10, or Del during boot) and check the keyboard settings.\n\nIf none of these solutions work, consider reaching out to a technician or the manufacturer for further assistance or repairs.",
